<article>
    <h1>HOW TECH&#xAD;NOL&#xAD;OGY IS DRIV&#xAD;ING CON&#xAD;STRUC&#xAD;TION SAFETY STAN&#xAD;DARDS</h1>
    <h2>ES&#xAD;THER TEO dis&#xAD;cov&#xAD;ers how the tra&#xAD;di&#xAD;tion&#xAD;ally labour-in&#xAD;ten&#xAD;sive con&#xAD;struc&#xAD;tion in&#xAD;dus&#xAD;try is em&#xAD;brac&#xAD;ing dig&#xAD;i&#xAD;tal tech&#xAD;nol&#xAD;ogy to meet unique health and safety re&#xAD;quire&#xAD;ments</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-09"><time>2020-11-09</time></a>
        - <span>PLACE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>From the an­cient won­ders of the world like the pyra­mids to mod­ern mar­vels such as the world’s tallest build­ing, the Burj Khal­ifa, the con­struc­tion in­dus­try has evolved with civilisati­ons — im­press­ing ev­ery gen­er­a­tion with feats of ar­chi­tec­tural bril­liance, and re­defin­ing our ev­ery­day lives with the build­ing of our homes, train sta­tions, schools and malls.</p>
    <p>Yet, for all its achieve­ments and ad­vances over the cen­turies, con­struc­tion work still re­mains labour-in­ten­sive and one of the most dan­ger­ous jobs today. Recog­nis­ing that an in­vest­ment in the safety of work­ers and part­ners is nec­es­sary for the long-term sus­tain­abil­ity of the busi­ness, more con­struc­tion com­pa­nies are adopt­ing in­creas­ingly so­phis­ti­cated tech­nol­ogy to drive work pro­cesses.</p>
    <p>Now that more than 90 per cent of con­struc­tion projects have been ap­proved to re­sume work as of mid-Au­gust, the re­cent launch of a $20-mil­lion Ad­vanced Dig­i­tal So­lu­tions</p>
    <p>scheme to off­set the costs of adopt­ing ad­vanced dig­i­tal so­lu­tions to help keep work­sites safe will no doubt be wel­comed.</p>
    <p>The scheme is sup­ported by the Build­ing and Con­struc­tion Author­ity and the In­fo­comm Me­dia Devel­op­ment Author­ity. It fol­lows the govern­ment’s $1.36 bil­lion Con­struc­tion Sup­port Pack­age rolled out in June.</p>
    <p>Ac­cord­ing to an ar­ti­cle in The Straits Times, the ini­tia­tive pro­vides fund­ing for up to 80 per cent of the cost of dig­i­tal equip­ment (sub­ject to a cap of $200,000 per firm) such as ther­mal scan­ners, bio­met­ric fa­cial recog­ni­tion sys­tems, ar­ti­fi­cial in­tel­li­gence cam­eras and Blue­tooth-en­abled wear­ables.</p>
    <p>At its launch, Na­tional Devel­op­ment Min­is­ter Des­mond Lee noted that de­spite mak­ing good progress in restart­ing work, the con­struc­tion sec­tor re­mains at risk of Covid-19 in­fec­tions, and must con­tinue to im­prove work pro­cesses to re­main vi­able.</p>

